+# Acceptance Criteria for a Real ION Portable GPT Engine Package
+
+A package may be called an ION Portable GPT engine only if it satisfies these criteria.
+
+## Required Operating Organs
+
+- [ ] Core law: AI output is not state.
+- [ ] User/Steward acceptance boundary.
+- [ ] Single-carrier GPT runtime.
+- [ ] Internal role sequence.
+- [ ] Context package and context-load proof.
+- [ ] Source authority classification.
+- [ ] Template/action/proof law.
+- [ ] Receipt law and package state update law.
+- [ ] Portable package import/resume/export protocol.
+- [ ] Diff/candidate delta protocol.
+- [ ] Carrier friction ledger.
+- [ ] Non-claims and safety boundaries.
+- [ ] Starter user package.
+- [ ] Knowledge manifest and GPT Builder instructions.
+- [ ] Source extracts proving lineage from existing ION package.
+
+## Required Exclusions
+
+- [ ] No historical donor archive as active law.
+- [ ] No Mini/Capsule as active context authority.
+- [ ] No Cursor subagent assumption as GPT baseline.
+- [ ] No local MCP/gateway/Codex requirement for base demo.
+- [ ] No production or live execution authority.
+- [ ] No claims that a generated package is accepted source truth.
+
+## Operational Test
+
+A fresh Custom GPT using this package should be able to:
+
+1. Start with "What are we working on?"
+2. Ingest uploaded project/company material.
+3. Classify source authority.
+4. Create a portable user package.
+5. Record accepted decisions as receipts.
+6. Export an updated package.
+7. Resume from that package in a fresh chat.
+8. Record friction events when workflow ambiguity appears.
+9. Explain diffs as candidate deltas.
+10. Refuse to claim state without receipts.

